  <static seed="1602" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations27.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {-\frac{4}{y+4}}={-\left(\frac{3}{y-4}+\frac{6}{y^{2}-16}\right)}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{34\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {-\frac{4}{y+4}} \amp = {-\left(\frac{3}{y-4}+\frac{6}{y^{2}-16}\right)} \\
  {-\frac{4}{y+4}} \amp = {-\frac{3}{y-4}-\frac{6}{\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)}} \\
  {-\frac{4}{y+4}\mathopen{}\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)} \amp = {-\frac{3}{y-4}\mathopen{}\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)-\frac{6}{\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)}\mathopen{}\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)} \\
  {-4\mathopen{}\left(y-4\right)} \amp = {-3\mathopen{}\left(y+4\right)-6} \\
  {-4y+16} \amp = {-3y-12-6} \\
  {-4y+16} \mathbf{  + 3y  - 16} \amp = {-3y-12-6} \mathbf{  + 3y  - 16} \\
  {-y} \amp = {-34} \\
  (-1) \cdot (-y) \amp = (-1) \cdot (-34) \\
  y \amp = 34
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp y^{2}-16 = 0 \amp \;\amp  y+4=0 \amp \;\amp  y-4=0 \\
   \amp (y+4)(y-4) = 0 \amp \;\amp  y=-4 \amp \;\amp  y=4 \\
   \amp y+4=0 \:\: or \:\: y-4=0 \\
   \amp y=-4 \:\: or \:\: y=4 \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>-4</m> and <m>4</m> from the solution set. These values are not in the solution set we got, so the final solution is <m>y=34</m>.</p>
</solution>
